---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Men's Clothing PLP — Myprotein">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Men's Clothing PLP</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Category Listing Page &mdash; Audited 4 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the All Men's Gym Clothes listing page at
      <code>/c/clothing/mens/view-the-whole-range/</code>, which surfaces 480 products across an
      infinite-scroll grid. The page has solid structural bones — a sticky filter bar, a scrollable
      subcategory pill row, and a prominent Quick Buy CTA on every card — but is let down by two
      high-severity content errors that will confuse shoppers and erode trust, plus a filter bar whose
      labels are systematically truncated, making filtering difficult to discover. Mobile tap targets
      on colour swatches are critically undersized. Design token drift on button size and card radius
      is minor but adds up across the range.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Wrong promo banner copy on product cards — nutrition brand tagline"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="wrong-promo-banner-nutrition"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Several product cards in the men's clothing grid display the banner:
        <strong>"UP TO 50% OFF | UK &amp; EUROPE'S NO. 1 SPORTS NUTRITION BRAND"</strong>.
        This is Myprotein's nutrition brand credential — it has no relevance on a clothing PLP and is
        actively misleading. The copy appears to be pulled from a global promotional template that
        hasn't been scoped to page type. Nutrition-branded messaging sitting beneath a gym hoodie
        card undermines both propositions.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A shopper browsing clothing who reads "Sports Nutrition Brand" as the core value proposition
        may question whether they're on the right page. It signals a content error, not an offer, and
        is likely to reduce confidence in the page. This also contradicts the delivery copy on
        adjacent cards, creating two competing messages in the same viewport.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Scope the promo banner template so that the "Sports Nutrition Brand" credential is suppressed
        on all clothing category pages (<code>/c/clothing/</code>). Replace with a clothing-specific
        offer if one exists (e.g. "UP TO 50% OFF CLOTHING | SHOP THE SALE"), or remove the banner
        entirely on clothing PLPs. This is a CMS/template config change — no design work required.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Filter labels truncated — users cannot identify filter type"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="filter-labels-truncated"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The sticky filter bar shows five filter dropdowns but truncates three of them at desktop
        (1440px): <strong>"Sport Clot..."</strong>, <strong>"Shop By S..."</strong>, and
        <strong>"Colour Ran..."</strong> are cut off mid-word. Only "Sort" and "Clothing Size" are
        fully visible. The filter bar uses a fixed layout at <code>1440px</code> without enough
        allocated width per filter to render full labels.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Truncated labels force users to click a filter to find out what it does — adding a redundant
        step and burying filtering capability behind interaction. This is a direct conversion
        friction: a user wanting to filter by colour must guess that "Colour Ran..." means Colour
        Range. With 480 results, effective filtering is critical to reaching an add-to-bag moment.
        On narrower screens the truncation will be even worse.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Shorten the filter labels to fit the available width without truncation. Suggested labels:
        "Sport" / "Activity", "Size", "Colour", rather than "Sport Clothing Type", "Shop By Size",
        "Colour Range". Alternatively, increase the available width per filter or reduce the number
        of visible filters at this breakpoint with overflow into a "More Filters" panel. Abbreviation
        or iconography (e.g. a colour wheel for colour) is also valid.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="'Free Delivery on New-In' banner shown on sale items"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="new-in-banner-on-sale-items"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The product card promo strip "FREE DELIVERY ON ALL NEW-IN WHEN YOU SPEND £30 | AUTO APPLIES
        AT CHECKOUT" appears on items that are clearly on sale — showing "Was £38.00 | Save £10.01"
        or similar — and are not new arrivals. The banner is being applied to all cards rather than
        only those tagged as new-in stock. Affected examples include sale-priced Rest Day Hoodies and
        Oversized Joggers at the top of the grid.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Contradictory messaging — "New In" banner + sale pricing — signals a content error to
        informed shoppers. It makes the delivery offer feel unreliable (which offer actually applies?)
        and could lead to cart abandonment if the delivery incentive is removed at checkout. It also
        dilutes the "new arrival" signal, which is one of the strongest impulse drivers in clothing
        retail.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Gate the "Free Delivery on New-In" banner on the <code>isNewIn</code> product attribute (or
        equivalent tag in the product data). Sale items should show a sale-specific message or no
        promo strip. This is a card template / product data conditional — it should not require a
        design change.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Colour swatches 24×24px — critically undersized tap target on mobile"
      viewport="Mobile"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="swatch-tap-target"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Individual colour swatch dots on product cards measure <strong>24×24px</strong>
        (confirmed via <code>getBoundingClientRect()</code>). WCAG 2.5.5 (Level AAA) recommends
        44×44px and Apple HIG requires 44pt minimum. At 24px, the interactive area is 55% smaller
        than the minimum recommended target.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Clothing shoppers heavily rely on colour selection as a pre-navigation filter — tapping a
        swatch to see the product in a different colour is a core interaction on mobile. A 24px target
        on a 390px screen requires excessive precision and will generate mis-taps, leading to
        accidental navigation or frustration. This disproportionately affects users on smaller phones
        and those with motor impairments.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Increase the swatch tap target to a minimum of 44×44px by adding padding or increasing the
        visual swatch size. If the visual size needs to stay at 24px for aesthetic reasons, wrap each
        swatch in a 44px-tall touch target container with transparent padding (e.g.
        <code>min-width: 44px; min-height: 44px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;</code>).
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy CTA missing brand-signature mint outer ring"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quick-buy-missing-mint-ring"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Quick Buy button has <code>box-shadow: none</code> — the mint (<code>#94E5B5</code>)
        outer ring that defines the Myprotein primary CTA signature is absent. The button renders
        with the correct dark teal background and 32px border-radius but without the ring that
        distinguishes the primary action visually.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The mint ring is a brand-level design decision that signals "this is the primary action" at a
        glance and makes the CTA visually distinctive against the product card backgrounds. Its
        absence on the most-used CTA across 480 product cards is a consistency gap that weakens the
        visual hierarchy, and it means the PLP CTA does not match the PDP Add to Basket button style.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add the mint outer ring as a box-shadow to the <code>.quick-buy-btn</code> (or equivalent
        class):
        <code>box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px #94E5B5;</code>. Verify this is applied consistently across
        all product card CTAs, not just the first in the DOM.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Wishlist button 40×40px — marginally below tap target minimum"
      viewport="Mobile"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="wishlist-tap-target"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The wishlist heart icon button on each product card measures <strong>40×40px</strong>. This
        is 4px short of the 44×44px minimum. The button uses class
        <code>plp-wishlist-btn ... p-2</code> — padding of 8px accounts for most of the tap area
        but falls just short.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The wishlist action is used frequently on mobile for shortlisting. At 40px the risk of
        mis-tapping is low but measurable, particularly in the corner position (top-right of each
        card) where thumb reach varies. WCAG 2.5.5 sets 44px as the benchmark.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Increase padding from <code>p-2</code> (8px) to <code>p-[10px]</code> or equivalent to
        bring the touch target to 44×44px. Alternatively use <code>min-w-[44px] min-h-[44px]</code>
        utility classes.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product card border-radius 16px vs design token 12px"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="card-border-radius-drift"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Product cards use <code>border-radius: 16px</code> (computed). The design system token
        <code>--radius-card</code> is defined as <strong>12px</strong>. The card uses Tailwind class
        <code>rounded-t-2xl</code> at <code>lg:</code> breakpoint (16px) rather than
        <code>rounded-t-xl</code> (12px equivalent).
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        4px of radius drift is subtle but accumulates across a high-density grid of 28+ cards.
        Where the PLP card style is referenced alongside PDP or basket cards, the inconsistency
        becomes visible. More importantly, if the design system token is updated, this component
        won't inherit the change automatically.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Align the card to use the design token value (12px / <code>rounded-xl</code>) or update the
        design token to reflect the intended 16px value and apply it consistently. This needs a
        design decision before engineering can act.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy font size 16px vs spec 14px Bold"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="button-font-size-drift"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Quick Buy button renders at <code>font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700</code>. The design
        system specifies button text as <strong>14px Bold</strong>. The button also has
        <code>padding: 10px 16px</code> which is within the valid spacing scale.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        At 16px the button label is proportionally large relative to the card, making the product
        title and price feel secondary. 14px Bold would keep the CTA prominent while restoring
        visual hierarchy within the card. Consistent button sizing also ensures the button renders
        at the same height across all page templates.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the Quick Buy button CSS to <code>font-size: 14px</code>. Verify across all
        breakpoints — the current 16px may be intentional for mobile legibility, in which case the
        design token should be updated to reflect this.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="SEO intro paragraph delays first product below the fold"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="seo-text-above-fold"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The page renders a two-sentence SEO description block ("Investing in the right
        activewear...") plus a "Read More" link above the subcategory pills and filter bar. At
        1440px this consumes ~130px of vertical space. The first product card is not visible until
        users scroll past the H1, SEO text, subcategory pills, and filter bar — approximately 700px
        from the top on desktop, and further on mobile.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        On a high-intent browsing page, the primary job is to show products. The SEO text serves
        crawlers, not shoppers. Users arriving from ads or search expecting to see clothing will
        encounter two lines of brand copy before any product. On mobile the problem is amplified —
        the full viewport may be consumed by header, breadcrumb, H1, SEO text, and pill row before
        any product card appears.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Collapse the SEO block to zero height by default and expose it via "Read More" only.
        Alternatively move it below the product grid (common pattern: SEO copy in a collapsed
        accordion at the bottom of the page). The H1 can remain visible for SEO purposes without
        the description needing to be above the fold.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product title repeats colour name already shown in swatches"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="title-colour-redundancy"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        All product titles follow the pattern: "MP Men's [Product Name] - [Colour]" (e.g.
        "MP Men's Rest Day Oversized Hoodie - Cornflower Blue"). The active colour is also
        shown visually via the colour swatch row directly above the title. The colour is conveyed
        twice — once in the swatch, once in the title — creating visual noise.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The colour suffix makes titles longer, causes wrapping to two lines on some cards, and
        creates vertical height inconsistency across the grid. Shorter titles would allow for a more
        compact, scannable card layout and reduce the visual weight of the text block beneath each
        image. This is low priority because it doesn't block purchase, but it degrades scannability
        across 480 products.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Display the active colour name as a smaller secondary label below the product title (or as
        a tooltip/label on the active swatch) and remove it from the title string itself. Requires
        a design decision on how to surface the active colour, and a CMS/template change to strip
        the suffix from the card title render.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The page uses Figtree throughout (confirmed via computed styles) and the core colour palette
      is consistent with the design system — dark teal (<code>oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code>,
      approximately <code>#003942</code>) on the Quick Buy button and price text, warm neutral card
      backgrounds. However, three token deviations were found: (1) card border-radius is 16px versus
      the <code>--radius-card</code> token of 12px; (2) the Quick Buy button renders at 16px font
      size versus the 14px Bold spec; and (3) the mint <code>#94E5B5</code> outer ring is absent
      from the primary CTA. The subcategory pill row uses 32px border-radius with a warm neutral
      fill — this is consistent with the pill token. No hardcoded colour values outside the token
      palette were detected on inspected elements. The H1 at 48px/700 is technically on the type
      scale but feels heavy for a category listing context compared with the 36px used on
      comparable PLPs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The most significant accessibility issue is the colour swatch tap target at 24×24px —
      this fails WCAG 2.5.5 (Target Size, Level AAA) and falls below Apple and Android HIG minimums.
      The wishlist button at 40×40px is marginally below WCAG 2.5.5. Body text and price text appear
      to meet 4.5:1 contrast on the warm neutral card background based on visual inspection of the
      dark teal on cream. The promo banners use all-caps text — this is readable but can be difficult
      for users with dyslexia; this is noted rather than flagged as a blocker. No obvious keyboard
      focus or screen reader issues were detected during the audit, but a full keyboard traversal
      was not completed. The product image alt text pattern and ARIA labelling on swatches were not
      inspected in depth and would benefit from a dedicated accessibility audit.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The path to Quick Buy is short and clear — the CTA is prominent on every card, the sticky
      filter bar allows refinement without losing scroll position, and the subcategory pills let
      users jump to sub-ranges efficiently. These are genuine strengths. The conversion risks are
      concentrated in trust and clarity: the wrong promo banner copy ("Sports Nutrition Brand" on
      clothing cards) is the most damaging finding as it signals a content error and can cause
      shoppers to question whether they are in the right place. The "New-In delivery offer" appearing
      on sale items creates a second trust gap. Truncated filter labels mean the full filtering
      capability of the page is hidden behind a click — with 480 products, users who can't find
      their size or colour quickly will bounce rather than scroll. Fix the two content errors first;
      they require no design work and would have an immediate impact.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>
        <strong>Suppress nutrition brand tagline on clothing PLPs</strong> — CMS/template config
        change, no design needed. Highest trust impact for lowest effort.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Gate "New-In delivery banner" on new-in product tag only</strong> — conditional
        template change. Removes contradictory messaging on sale items immediately.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fix truncated filter labels</strong> — shorten label strings or widen filter
        dropdown widths. Directly improves discoverability for 480-product catalogue browsing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Increase colour swatch tap target to 44px</strong> — CSS padding change.
        Significantly improves mobile usability for colour-led shopping.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add mint outer ring to Quick Buy button</strong> — single CSS
        <code>box-shadow</code> addition. Restores brand signature CTA consistency.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Increase wishlist button to 44×44px</strong> — padding tweak.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Collapse SEO intro text by default</strong> — move product grid closer to the fold.
        Design decision required first.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Resolve card border-radius and button font-size token drift</strong> — design
        decision on intended values, then a single CSS update.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
